d political processes that drove the rise of the United States as a capitalist world power long before the onset of globalization. Spanning the course of U.S. history, these crucial essays show how the return of racism and war as seemingly permanent features of American public and political life is at the heart of our present crisis and collective disorientation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aNational characteristics, AmericanxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aafrican slavery. 4aamerican history. 4afar right. 4ahuman rights advocates. 4aimmigrant relations. 4aimmigrant studies. 4apolitical climate. 4apolitical science. 4apoly sci major. 4aracially homogenous. 4aracism in the united states. 4areligious right. 4aus mexico border. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2017z978311066755408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520968837423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520968837.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066755-4  UC Press eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles